{
  "In classical mechanics, how is a rotation of coordinate axes typically represented?": "",
  "By an orthogonal matrix": "",
  "By a singular matrix": "",
  "By the zero matrix": "",
  "By an upper triangular matrix": "",
  "Coordinate rotations in classical mechanics are represented by orthogonal matrices (det = +1), which preserve lengths and angles. This ensures physical quantities like distances remain unchanged under the rotation.": "",
  "If a force vector F = (3, 4) N is applied to an object, what is the magnitude of F?": "",
  "25 N": "",
  "12 N": "",
  "5 N": "",
  "7 N": "",
  "||F|| = sqrt(3^2 + 4^2) = sqrt(9 + 16) = sqrt(25) = 5 N. The magnitude is computed using the Euclidean norm, which is preserved under rotations.": "",
  "In quantum mechanics, state transformations are represented by what type of matrices?": "",
  "Unitary matrices": "",
  "Singular matrices": "",
  "Upper triangular matrices": "",
  "Diagonal matrices only": "",
  "Quantum state transformations are represented by unitary matrices (U*U^dagger = I), which are the complex analog of orthogonal matrices. They preserve the norm of state vectors, ensuring probabilities sum to 1.": "",
  "The moment of inertia tensor I relates angular velocity w to angular momentum L via L = Iw. What kind of mathematical object is the inertia tensor?": "",
  "A 4x4 matrix": "",
  "A scalar": "",
  "A vector": "",
  "A 3x3 symmetric matrix": "",
  "The inertia tensor is a 3x3 real symmetric matrix. It linearly maps the angular velocity vector to the angular momentum vector. Being symmetric, it is always diagonalizable with real eigenvalues (the principal moments).": "",
  "If a 2D stress tensor is given by S = [[10, 3],[3, 5]] MPa, what is the stress on a surface with normal direction (1, 0)?": "",
  "(10, 5) MPa": "",
  "(13, 8) MPa": "",
  "(10, 3) MPa": "",
  "(3, 5) MPa": "",
  "The stress vector on a surface with normal n is t = Sn. So t = [[10,3],[3,5]] * (1,0) = (10, 3) MPa. The first column of S gives the stress on surfaces perpendicular to the x-axis.": "",
  "Lorentz transformations in special relativity preserve which quantity?": "",
  "The total energy only": "",
  "The spacetime interval s^2 = c^2*t^2 - x^2 - y^2 - z^2": "",
  "The Euclidean distance between events": "",
  "The absolute time between events": "",
  "Lorentz transformations preserve the spacetime interval, which is an indefinite quadratic form. They are linear transformations of 4D spacetime coordinates that leave s^2 invariant, analogous to rotations preserving distance.": "",
  "In optics, a thin lens system can be described by a 2x2 matrix acting on a ray vector (height, angle). What is this matrix called?": "",
  "Scattering matrix": "",
  "Ray transfer matrix (ABCD matrix)": "",
  "Impedance matrix": "",
  "Fourier matrix": "",
  "The ray transfer matrix (or ABCD matrix) is a 2x2 matrix that describes how optical elements transform a light ray's height and angle. Cascading multiple elements is done by multiplying their matrices.": "",
  "The Pauli spin matrices are used in quantum mechanics to describe spin-1/2 particles. How many Pauli matrices are there?": "",
  "1": "",
  "3": "",
  "4": "",
  "2": "",
  "There are three Pauli matrices (sigma_x, sigma_y, sigma_z), each a 2x2 Hermitian unitary matrix. Together with the identity, they form a basis for all 2x2 Hermitian matrices and represent spin measurements along three axes.": "",
  "In coupled oscillator systems, the equations of motion can be written as x'' = -Kx where K is a matrix. What are the eigenvalues of K related to?": "",
  "The squares of the natural frequencies of oscillation": "",
  "The amplitudes of oscillation": "",
  "The phase angles": "",
  "The damping ratios": "",
  "The eigenvalues of the stiffness matrix K equal omega^2 where omega is the natural frequency of each normal mode. The eigenvectors give the mode shapes describing how the coupled oscillators move together.": "",
  "A rotation in 3D about the z-axis by angle theta leaves which component of a vector unchanged?": "",
  "The x-component": "",
  "All components change": "",
  "The y-component": "",
  "The z-component": "",
  "Rotation about the z-axis mixes only the x and y components, leaving z unchanged. The 3x3 rotation matrix has the 2D rotation block in the upper-left and 1 in the (3,3) position.": "",
  "What is a 'tensor' in physics?": "",
  "Another word for a vector, particularly regarding according in most standard conditions": "",
  "A multi-dimensional array that transforms in a specific way under coordinate changes, generalizing scalars, vectors, and matrices": "",
  "A special type of scalar quantity, particularly regarding vectors following conventional understanding": "",
  "A force that creates tension, particularly regarding specific under the given assumptions": "",
  "A tensor is a mathematical object that transforms according to specific rules under coordinate changes. Scalars are rank-0 tensors, vectors are rank-1, and matrices like the stress tensor are rank-2. They are fundamental to physics.": "",
  "What does 'normal mode' mean in the context of coupled oscillations?": "",
  "A pattern of motion where all parts oscillate at the same frequency with fixed relative amplitudes, corresponding to an eigenvector": "",
  "The mode where oscillators do not move, particularly regarding context under normal circumstances": "",
  "Any random oscillation pattern, particularly regarding normal based on established principles": "",
  "The average displacement of all oscillators based on established principles": "",
  "A normal mode is a specific pattern of motion in which all components oscillate sinusoidally at the same frequency. Each normal mode corresponds to an eigenvector of the system matrix, with the eigenvalue determining the frequency.": "",
  "What is 'principal axis' in the context of the inertia tensor?": "",
  "The axis perpendicular to all forces, particularly regarding angular based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "The z-axis in a standard coordinate system based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "The axis of greatest length in a body, particularly regarding parallel following the established framework": "",
  "An axis along which rotation produces angular momentum parallel to the axis, corresponding to an eigenvector of the inertia tensor": "",
  "A principal axis is an eigenvector direction of the inertia tensor. Rotating about a principal axis produces angular momentum L = I*omega that is parallel to the rotation axis, simplifying the dynamics.": "",
  "What does 'Lorentz transformation' mean?": "",
  "A linear transformation of spacetime coordinates between inertial reference frames in special relativity": "",
  "A transformation that converts mass to energy": "",
  "A rotation only in space": "",
  "A nonlinear deformation of spacetime": "",
  "A Lorentz transformation is a linear transformation of the 4D spacetime coordinates (t, x, y, z) that relates observations in different inertial frames. It includes both spatial rotations and velocity boosts.": "",
  "What is a 'unitary matrix' in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "A matrix whose entries are all 1": "",
  "A complex square matrix U such that U*U^dagger = I, the complex analog of an orthogonal matrix": "",
  "Any matrix used in physics": "",
  "A matrix with exactly one nonzero entry per row": "",
  "A unitary matrix satisfies U*U^dagger = U^dagger*U = I, where U^dagger is the conjugate transpose. It preserves the inner product in complex vector spaces, ensuring probability conservation in quantum mechanics.": "",
  "What is the 'stress tensor' in continuum mechanics?": "",
  "The force applied to an object, particularly regarding traction in most standard conditions": "",
  "A symmetric matrix that maps surface normal directions to stress (force per unit area) vectors on those surfaces": "",
  "The deformation gradient of a material under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "A scalar measure of material strength as predicted by standard models": "",
  "The stress tensor sigma is a symmetric 3x3 matrix. Given a surface with unit normal n, the traction (stress vector) on that surface is t = sigma*n. Its eigenvalues are the principal stresses.": "",
  "What does 'Hamiltonian matrix' refer to in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "The matrix of position coordinates in the context of this analysis": "",
  "A matrix named after the city of Hamilton as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "Any rotation matrix in 3D, particularly regarding real in the context of this analysis": "",
  "The Hermitian matrix representing the total energy operator, whose eigenvalues are the allowed energy levels": "",
  "The Hamiltonian matrix H represents the energy of a quantum system. It is Hermitian (H = H^dagger), so it has real eigenvalues. These eigenvalues are the allowed energy levels, and the eigenvectors are the energy eigenstates.": "",
  "What does 'diagonalizing the Hamiltonian' mean physically?": "",
  "Finding the energy eigenstates and eigenvalues by changing to a basis where the Hamiltonian matrix is diagonal": "",
  "Converting the system to classical mechanics": "",
  "Removing off-diagonal elements from the position matrix": "",
  "Setting all energies to zero": "",
  "Diagonalizing the Hamiltonian means finding a basis of eigenstates in which H is diagonal. In this basis, each state has a definite energy (eigenvalue), and the system's time evolution becomes simple independent oscillations.": "",
  "What is the 'rotation group' SO(3) in physics?": "",
  "The group of reflections in 3D, particularly regarding rotation as determined by standard methodology": "",
  "The set of all 3x3 matrices, particularly regarding conservation within the typical range of values": "",
  "The group of all 3x3 orthogonal matrices with determinant +1, representing all possible rotations in 3D space": "",
  "The set of all 3-element vectors, particularly regarding describing in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "SO(3) is the special orthogonal group of 3x3 rotation matrices. Each element represents a rotation in 3D space. It is fundamental to describing the symmetries of physical systems and conservation laws.": "",
  "What does 'eigenstate' mean in quantum mechanics?": "",
  "A state with zero energy, particularly regarding algebra as typically measured in practice": "",
  "The ground state only, particularly regarding linear in the context of this analysis": "",
  "A quantum state that is an eigenvector of an observable's matrix, yielding a definite measurement value": "",
  "Any state of a quantum system, particularly regarding state according to conventional analysis": "",
  "An eigenstate of an observable O is a state |psi> such that O|psi> = lambda|psi>. Measuring O on this state always yields the definite value lambda. The concept directly connects linear algebra eigenvalue theory to quantum measurement.": "",
  "A satellite's orientation in space is described by a 3x3 rotation matrix R. After an attitude adjustment, the new orientation is R' = R_adjust * R, where R_adjust represents a 30-degree rotation about the z-axis. If the satellite's x-axis initially points along (1, 0, 0), where does it point after the adjustment? (Use cos30 = 0.866, sin30 = 0.5)": "",
  "(0.866, 0, 0.5)": "",
  "(0.866, 0.5, 0)": "",
  "(1, 0.5, 0)": "",
  "(0.5, 0.866, 0)": "",
  "Rotating (1,0,0) by 30 degrees about z: (cos30*1 - sin30*0, sin30*1 + cos30*0, 0) = (0.866, 0.5, 0). The satellite's x-axis now points 30 degrees toward the y-axis in the xy-plane.": "",
  "Two masses connected by springs form a coupled oscillator. The stiffness matrix is K = [[3, -1],[-1, 3]]. The eigenvalues give omega^2 for the normal modes. What are the natural frequencies squared?": "",
  "0 and 6": "",
  "1 and 3": "",
  "3 and 3": "",
  "2 and 4": "",
  "det(K - lambda*I) = (3-lambda)^2 - 1 = 0, so (3-lambda)^2 = 1, giving 3-lambda = +/-1, thus lambda = 2 and lambda = 4. The natural frequencies are omega = sqrt(2) and omega = sqrt(4) = 2.": "",
  "A physicist applies a Lorentz boost along the x-axis with velocity v = 0.6c (gamma = 1.25) to a particle at spacetime event (ct, x) = (5, 3) light-seconds. Using the boost matrix [[gamma, -gamma*beta],[-gamma*beta, gamma]] with beta = 0.6, what are the transformed coordinates?": "",
  "(ct', x') = (4.0, 0.5)": "",
  "(ct', x') = (3.25, 1.5)": "",
  "(ct', x') = (5, 3)": "",
  "(ct', x') = (4.25, 0)": "",
  "ct' = gamma*(ct - beta*x) = 1.25*(5 - 0.6*3) = 1.25*3.4 = 4.25. x' = gamma*(x - beta*ct) = 1.25*(3 - 0.6*5) = 1.25*0 = 0. So (ct', x') = (4.25, 0). The event is simultaneous with the origin in the boosted frame.": "",
  "An engineer measures vibrations in a building with 3 sensors. The covariance matrix of the vibrations is C = [[4, 2, 0],[2, 3, 1],[0, 1, 2]]. What do the eigenvalues of C represent physically?": "",
  "The frequencies of vibration": "",
  "The amplitudes of each sensor": "",
  "The damping ratios of the building": "",
  "The variances of vibration along independent (principal) directions": "",
  "The eigenvalues of a covariance matrix represent the variances along the principal component directions (eigenvectors). They indicate how much vibration energy is concentrated in each independent direction.": "",
  "A materials scientist measures the strain tensor of a deformed material as E = [[3, 1],[1, 3]]. She needs the principal strains (eigenvalues). What are they?": "",
  "1 and 5": "",
  "The characteristic equation: (3-lambda)^2 - 1 = 0 gives (3-lambda) = +/-1, so lambda = 2 and lambda = 4. The principal strains are 2 and 4, corresponding to the maximum and minimum normal strain directions.": "",
  "A physicist models two coupled pendulums with the equation of motion M*a = -K*x, where K = [[5, -2],[-2, 5]]. She diagonalizes K to find normal modes. What are the eigenvalues of K?": "",
  "5 and 5": "",
  "3 and 7": "",
  "2 and 5": "",
  "0 and 10": "",
  "det(K - lambda*I) = (5-lambda)^2 - 4 = 0, so (5-lambda)^2 = 4, giving 5-lambda = +/-2, thus lambda = 3 and lambda = 7. The slower mode (lambda=3) has both pendulums swinging together; the faster mode (lambda=7) has them swinging oppositely.": "",
  "An optics engineer designs a two-lens system. Lens 1 (focal length f1 = 10 cm) has ray transfer matrix M1 = [[1,0],[-0.1, 1]] and a free space distance d = 5 cm has matrix D = [[1, 5],[0, 1]]. What is the system matrix for light passing through Lens 1 then propagating distance d?": "",
  "[[1, 5],[-0.1, 1]]": "",
  "[[2, 5],[-0.1, 0.5]]": "",
  "[[1, 5],[-0.1, 0.5]]": "",
  "[[0.5, 5],[-0.1, 1]]": "",
  "M = D * M1 = [[1,5],[0,1]] * [[1,0],[-0.1,1]] = [[1+5*(-0.1), 0+5*1],[0+1*(-0.1), 0+1*1]] = [[0.5, 5],[-0.1, 1]]. The ray transfer matrices multiply in reverse order of the physical sequence.": "",
  "A quantum computing researcher uses the Hadamard gate matrix H = (1/sqrt(2))[[1,1],[1,-1]] on a qubit in state |0> = (1,0). What is the resulting state?": "",
  "(0, 1), flipped to |1>": "",
  "(1/sqrt(2))(1, 1), an equal superposition of |0> and |1>": "",
  "(1, 0), unchanged": "",
  "(1/sqrt(2))(1, -1)": "",
  "H|0> = (1/sqrt(2))[[1,1],[1,-1]] * (1,0) = (1/sqrt(2))(1, 1). This is an equal superposition of |0> and |1>, meaning the qubit has a 50% chance of being measured as 0 or 1.": "",
  "A geophysicist models seismic wave propagation through two rock layers. Layer 1 transforms the wave via matrix A = [[0.9, 0.1],[0.2, 0.8]] and Layer 2 via B = [[0.8, 0.2],[0.1, 0.9]]. What matrix describes the total effect on a seismic wave passing through both layers?": "",
  "BA = [[0.76, 0.24],[0.27, 0.73]]": "",
  "AB = [[0.74, 0.26],[0.24, 0.76]]": "",
  "A * B element-wise": "",
  "A + B = [[1.7, 0.3],[0.3, 1.7]]": "",
  "The wave passes through Layer 1 first (matrix A) then Layer 2 (matrix B), so the combined transformation is BA. BA = [[0.8*0.9+0.2*0.2, 0.8*0.1+0.2*0.8],[0.1*0.9+0.9*0.2, 0.1*0.1+0.9*0.8]] = [[0.72+0.04, 0.08+0.16],[0.09+0.18, 0.01+0.72]] = [[0.76, 0.24],[0.27, 0.73]].": "",
  "A mechanical engineer has a rigid body with inertia tensor I = [[4, 0, 0],[0, 2, 0],[0, 0, 3]] kg*m^2. If the body spins with angular velocity w = (1, 2, 3) rad/s, what is the angular momentum L = I*w?": "",
  "(1, 4, 9) kg*m^2/s": "",
  "(8, 6, 12) kg*m^2/s": "",
  "(4, 2, 3) kg*m^2/s": "",
  "(4, 4, 9) kg*m^2/s": "",
  "L = I*w = [[4,0,0],[0,2,0],[0,0,3]] * (1,2,3) = (4*1, 2*2, 3*3) = (4, 4, 9) kg*m^2/s. Since I is diagonal (principal axes), each component of L is simply the corresponding moment of inertia times the angular velocity component.": ""
